 III. Defined
 
 
a. Project:
b. A unique endeavor, and usually includes a set of unique deliverables.
c. A temporary pursuit; it has a definded beginning and end. (Tracking and budget)
d. Project management:



The application of knowledge, skills, tools, and techniques to meet the project requirement and achieve the desired outcome.

Valuable to business because it helps ensure that a project delivers the expected outcomes.

- What does a project manager do?
- Planning and organizing
- Managing tasks
- Controlling costs and budgeting
- Other factors



Make sure the project outcome is bringing value to the company. It always is that on time and on budget. Sometimes, it might be a new services for customers or modifying
an old service (It’s more tailored to customer’s need).

A project manager’s daily responsibilities always include some version of the following, planing and organizing. She/ he always defines clearly:

- What exactly our project’s trying to accomplish
- Creating project plans is a key part of project management
      - Keep everyong on pace and aligned, helps move tasks along.
- Managing tasks:
      - Helps manage tasks for the team members and communicates key milestones to the larger team or customers
      - Help team member or customer updated on how the project is progressing.
- Budgeting and controlling costs and other factors.






 IV. Path to becoming a project manager
 
1. Why/what they were doing

Internship: A short-term way to get hands-on experience in the industry.

One of the key benefits of internships is that you get real work experience while simultaneously networking with people in that industry.


Contract work:

Working on contract for a company rather than being an official employee of a company, a contractor may be hired on a project-by-project basis.





V. IV. What are the possibilites?

Project management job categories and common roles.

1. Introductory-level project management roles

a. Junior project manager: perform all aspects of being a project manager alogside a more experienced professional
b. Project administrator: Assists the rest of the project team with administrative tasks.
c. Prject/ Program assistant: Supports team members working on a project and offers administrative support. May perform research or create training documents along with other
jobs as assigned by program leaders.
d. Project/Program coordinator: Participates in hands-on project work and administrative tasks. Works under a project manager to make sure projects are completed on time and
within budget.
e. Project support Specialist: works alongside a project manager and team members to oversee assigned projects. May also be responsible for training and developing employees
to perform designated tasks.




2. Traditional project management roles:

a. Project manager: Responsible for the initiating, planing, monitoring, and closing of a project. Includes industry-specific titles like IT project manger, construction
project manager or engineering project manager, which utilize skills that are transferable among industries.
b. Project analyst: Moves a project along by sharing information, providing support through data analysis, and contributing to strategy and performance.
c. Project Leader/director: Drives core decision-making and sets the direction for the project. Usually knowledgeable about the product of deliverable.
d. Project controller: Primarily responsible for project planing. You are likely to see this job title in industries like engineering and construction.
e. Technical Project manager: conducts project planning and management for identified goals within a company. Ensures that projects are completed to the requirements within 
a defined time frame and budget.
f. Prject management office (PMO) Analyst: Manges the process of complex projects to ensure timely excution and completion.






3. Program management roles

After having carried out projects successfully and next step is a prgram manger position.

a. Program manger: Program managers are essentially project managers but on a larger scale. They manage a group of projects that are similar or related to one another and
handle coordination across multiple projects that are used to meet a program’s main goals. They also create and manage long-term goals for an organization.
b. Portfolio manager: Responsible for managing a group of different programs or projects within the same organization. These projects or programs may be related to one 
another. Porfolio mangers look at all projects and programs, and prioritize work as necessary.





4. Operational management roles:

a. Operations analyst: manages and coordinates research, investigates workflows, creates business procedures, and recommends changes to improve the project and company.
b. Operations manager: Oversees strategic decision-making and rolls out plans of action based on financial, schedual, and resource reporting.
c. Chief Operation officer: responsible for overseeing the day-to-day administrative and operational functions of a business.




5. Agile Roles:

a. Scrum Master: coordinates and guides the scrum team. Knowledgeable in agile framework and scrum and is able to teach others about the Scrum values and principles
b. Product Owner: Drives the direction of product development and prgress.





Some skill requirements:

a. Organizational management
b. Strong planning and communication skills,
c. Budget preparetion and monitoring




Some tasks we will learn:

a. Monthly status reports
b. Implement new and necessary techologies
c. Tracking work plans and performance metrics
d. Assisting other members of the operational team
e. Ensuring timely responses to requests for information




Networking is when you meet other people in a professional setting with the goal of learning, sharing knowledge, and creating new business connections.

Using buzzwords and skills in your job search:

a. Coordination, or getting people and teams to work together.
  - Coordination of efforts to achieve project deliverable
  - Coordinate internal resources to ensure successful project completion
  
  
  
  
 managing the coordination of resources to achieve your end goal.

